nd":0.017751278315878236,"ani":0.02050954435743037,"unwel":0.017751278315878236}},{"type":"ceremony","data":{"id":3,"name":"Buganu — Marula Beer Festival","description":"Buganu is a joyful national ceremony held each year to celebrate the ripening of the marula fruit. Women across Eswatini brew traditional beer from the marula fruit and present it to the king at Ludzidzini royal village. The ceremony is largely women-led and celebrates the role of women in Swazi culture and agriculture. Thousands of women travel to the royal residence carrying calabashes of freshly brewed marula beer which is offered to the king as a gift from the nation. The king tastes the beer, signalling that it is acceptable, and celebrations begin. Buganu is a time of singing, dancing, and communal joy. It also serves as an important social occasion where women from different parts of the country come together. The marula tree holds special significance in Swazi culture and its fruit is regarded as a royal fruit with spiritual properties.","month_celebrated":"February","immunology_notes":"The marula beer presented during Buganu is a fermented beverage and contains alcohol. Participants who are pregnant or breastfeeding are advised not to consume the beer. The brewing process must follow traditional methods to ensure the beer does not spoil before the ceremony. Women who are unwell are encouraged to rest rather than undertake the long journey to the royal village. The marula fruit itself is rich in vitamin C and is considered to have nutritional and medicinal properties in traditional Swazi knowledge."},"vector":{"buganu":0.0636097490406115,"marula":0.11131706082107011,"beer":0.11131706082107011,"festiv":0.015902437260152873,"februari":0.020650020688645646,"joy":0.020650020688645646,"nation":0.020696241421451926,"ceremoni":0.03104436213217789,"held":0.017872862413932194,"each":0.020650020688645646,"year":0.017872862413932194,"celebr":0.03937583695631825,"ripen":0.020650020688645646,"fruit":0.07